    <h2>Concept Name: “Canvas & Code”</h2>
    <p>Tagline: "Where artistry meets pixels."</p>

    <p>
      Core Idea: Position your service as a digital atelier—a creative studio
      where your clients' visions are translated into vivid, handcrafted
      websites. Think of each site as a collaborative artwork: your client
      brings the inspiration, and you bring the technical brushstrokes.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <h2>Visual/Brand Mood:</h2>
      <li>Cozy, colorful, and whimsical</li>
      <li>Hand-drawn elements, textured backgrounds, natural shapes</li>
      <li>Soft, custom typography and pastel palettes</li>
    </ul>

    <ul>
      <h2>Key Features/Offers:</h2>
      <li>
        Portfolio-First Design: Build sites that feel like immersive galleries
        or journals.
      </li>
      <li>
        Storytelling Frameworks: Let creatives tell their brand story visually
        and emotionally.
      </li>
      <li>
        Creative Companion Calls: A process that feels more like an artist
        collaboration than a business transaction.
      </li>
      <li>
        “Palette Picker” Questionnaire: Help clients choose colors based on
        their work and style.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Unique Selling Point: You're not just designing websites—you’re
      co-creating digital homes for passionate people. You get their creative
      process because you share it.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <h2>Visual Style & Design Elements Think “boho meets browser”:</h2>
      <li>
        Color Palette: Muted earth tones, vintage pastels, and rich accent
        colors (like ochre, dusty rose, sage, ink blue)
      </li>
      <li>Textures: Paper grain, watercolor washes, layered collages</li>
      <li>
        Typography: Soft serif headlines (like Cormorant Garamond or Playfair) +
        friendly sans-serifs (like Quicksand or DM Sans)
      </li>
      <li>
        Illustration Style: Sketchy icons, line drawings of tools (paintbrushes,
        cameras, books, etc.), dotted borders and torn edges
      </li>
      <li>
        Microinteractions: Hover animations like brush strokes appearing, cursor
        turning into a paintbrush, loading screens with small “art studio”
        metaphors
      </li>
    </ul>

